to discuss supply chain analytics in the framework of descriptive, predictive, and prescriptive

00:06:09.320 --> 00:06:13.320
analytics. Now, descriptive analytics, the biggest and most important part of the pyramid

00:06:13.320 --> 00:06:17.320
includes business intelligence and diagnostic analytics of the supply chain. How many of

00:06:17.320 --> 00:06:21.320
my trucks arrived on time? How productive were my manufacturing plants in my warehouses?

00:06:21.320 --> 00:06:26.320
How are these metrics trending? And are any of them worrisome? Predictive analytics is

00:06:26.320 --> 00:06:29.320
next. How do we predict what's going to happen next in our supply chain? That includes things

00:06:29.320 --> 00:06:34.320
like sales forecasting, as we'll be discussing next, as well as forecasting costs for your

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:38.320
supply chain inputs and some types of supply chain simulation. Finally, the top of the

00:06:38.320 --> 00:06:42.320
pyramid, which by volume should occupy the least amount of time, is prescriptive analytics.

00:06:42.320 --> 00:06:46.320
What should I do with my supply chain? This is my wheelhouse, and it includes things like

00:06:46.320 --> 00:06:50.320
supply chain network design, discussed today, as well as inventory optimization and other

00:06:50.320 --> 00:06:56.320
types of supply chain simulation. Now, a key point for this audience, especially, is that

00:06:56.320 --> 00:07:00.320
open source technologies are really changing the landscape in supply chain management and

00:07:00.320 --> 00:07:04.320
supply chain analytics. When you look at each of these capabilities, you can mentally pick

00:07:04.320 --> 00:07:09.320
out which R or Python packages you could use for them. This really is a sea change from

00:07:09.320 --> 00:07:13.320
when I started in the supply chain analytics field about a decade ago, when the toolkit

00:07:13.320 --> 00:07:19.320
consisted of Excel for data analysis, SPSS for statistics, and commercial visualization

00:07:19.320 --> 00:07:26.320
software like Tableau. So, what is supply chain network design? Put plainly, it's the

00:07:26.320 --> 00:07:30.320
strategic analysis of the locations and activities of the various elements of a firm's supply

00:07:30.320 --> 00:07:35.320
chain. For example, if I'm a manufacturer, where should I locate warehouses for my raw

00:07:35.320 --> 00:07:40.320
materials, the stuff I use to make other stuff, or my semi-finished goods, which are items

00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:45.320
that are only partway through the manufacturing process? Where should I put my manufacturing

00:07:45.320 --> 00:07:49.320
facilities, my plants? Where should they go? Where should I put my distribution centers,

00:07:49.320 --> 00:07:56.320
my warehouses for finished goods? Where should they be located? And if I'm a retailer, how

00:07:56.320 --> 00:08:01.320
should I use my stores as a link in my supply chain? For example, many leading retailers,

00:08:01.320 --> 00:08:05.320
including my former employer, Target, use their stores as strategic assets for shipping

00:08:05.320 --> 00:08:09.320
e-commerce orders. Well, from where should we do that? That's a big question. That's a

00:08:09.320 --> 00:08:14.320
supply chain network design question. Supply chain network design seeks to answer these

00:08:14.320 --> 00:08:19.320
big questions, all with the intent to understand the impacts on profitability, cost, service,

00:08:19.320 --> 00:08:23.320
and other key metrics, and with the goal to minimize or maximize one or two key metrics,

00:08:23.320 --> 00:08:29.320
usually cost or profitability. Today, I'll be focusing on a relatively simple example

00:08:29.320 --> 00:08:34.320
of supply chain network design, a distribution network with two echelons, the distribution

00:08:34.320 --> 00:08:40.320
centers, or warehouses, and customers that are serviced by those warehouses. In designing

00:08:40.320 --> 00:08:44.320
a supply chain, we ask ourselves, given a customer base of demand aggregated to a city

00:08:44.320 --> 00:08:50.320
level, one, where should we open distribution centers to satisfy that demand? And two, what

00:08:50.320 --> 00:08:55.320
customers should be serviced by or aligned to each distribution center? While most real

00:08:55.320 --> 00:08:59.320
life supply chain design problems are much, much more complex than this example, I hope

00:08:59.320 --> 00:09:03.320
it will be informative on how practitioners approach these kinds of problems and how we

00:09:03.320 --> 00:09:09.320
can use open source technology for them. So how do we do this? How can we answer these

00:09:09.320 --> 00:09:13.320
questions? We can answer them with optimization modeling. Optimization modeling is a mathematical

00:09:13.320 --> 00:09:18.320
technique that allows a practitioner to optimize a set of interconnected decisions where the

00:09:18.320 --> 00:09:23.320
decisions are constrained by real world limitations. Optimization solvers take the decision options

00:09:23.320 --> 00:09:28.320
formulated as a mathematical model and return the set of decisions that optimizes, minimizes,

00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:33.320
or maximizes an equation that includes the decisions as inputs. This equation is formally

00:09:33.320 --> 00:09:38.320
known as an objective function. If anyone on here has an operations research background,

00:09:38.320 --> 00:09:42.320
I realize it's not the precise mathematical definition, but I find it to be useful in

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:47.320
explaining the field. So in our case, the decisions we need to make are one, how many

00:09:47.320 --> 00:09:51.320
distribution centers should open and where should we locate them? And two, what customers

00:09:51.320 --> 00:09:55.320
should align to each distribution center? You can see that these decisions, they're

00:09:55.320 --> 00:09:59.320
interconnected because I can't align a customer to a distribution center in a certain city

00:09:59.320 --> 00:10:04.320
unless I also open a distribution center in that city. And the limitations on our decisions

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:09.320
or our constraints, they're one, that all customer demand must be met. We may have a

00:10:09.320 --> 00:10:15.320
minimum or maximum number of distribution centers. We may really only realistically

00:10:15.320 --> 00:10:19.320
open distribution centers in certain locations. So we have to start with kind of a candidate

00:10:19.320 --> 00:10:25.320
set of cities. We may have a maximum volume per distribution center. That's also called

00:10:25.320 --> 00:10:31.320
the capacity. And for certain reasons, we may put a maximum distance between a customer

00:10:31.320 --> 00:10:35.320
and its servicing distribution center. And we'll see that later in an example. So we'll

00:10:35.320 --> 00:10:38.320
shortly transition to the Shiny app I built for the webinar. But first I'll introduce

00:10:38.320 --> 00:10:42.320
this scenario. Now, because this is a simplified scenario, this is a simplified version of

00:10:42.320 --> 00:10:49.320
an app I would use for a regular project. You are a supply chain data scientist at Heartland

00:10:49.320 --> 00:10:54.320
Widgets Incorporated. Your company is the market leader in widget sales across eight

00:10:54.320 --> 00:10:59.320
state area of the American Midwest. The pandemic-induced shift in consumer demand from services to

00:10:59.320 --> 00:11:03.320
goods, as well as stay-at-home orders, has led to a boom in demand for your company's

00:11:03.320 --> 00:11:08.320
flagship product, the at-home widget. Based with record demand, the Director of Supply Chain

00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:13.320
Network Planning has asked you to, quote, reimagine the company's distribution network.

00:11:13.320 --> 00:11:18.320
You are to recommend the where to open Heartland's distribution centers, as well as the customer

00:11:18.320 --> 00:11:24.320
to distribution center alignment, to achieve a minimal cost. Heartland Widgets has customers

00:11:25.320 --> 00:11:30.320
in 117 Midwestern cities, spread from the Dakotas in the west, all the way to my home

00:11:30.320 --> 00:11:34.320
state of Indiana in the east. Each city's demand is proportional to its population.

00:11:34.320 --> 00:11:38.320
So, for example, Chicago, Illinois, which is a big city, you may have heard of it, has

00:11:38.320 --> 00:11:45.320
more demand than Fargo, North Dakota. Heartland is considering 20 cities for potential distribution

00:11:45.320 --> 00:11:50.320
center sites. Because each distribution center will cost $1 million to open, it may not be

00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:54.320
cost effective to open distribution centers in all 20 cities, but we're keeping our options

00:11:54.320 --> 00:12:00.320
open. So, let's get a little bit more technical here. The decisions we need to make for Heartland

00:12:00.320 --> 00:12:05.320
Widgets can be represented by variables. When we ask, what customer should we align to which

00:12:05.320 --> 00:12:09.320
distribution center, this is equivalent to asking a set of yes-no decisions that must

00:12:09.320 --> 00:12:14.320
be made in concert. For each customer city I, should I service it by a distribution center

00:12:14.320 --> 00:12:20.320
in city J, yes or no? In making our decisions, we're limited to having exactly one yes per

00:12:20.320 --> 00:12:26.320
customer city. It has to be serviced by exactly one distribution center. Relatedly, we need

00:12:26.320 --> 00:12:30.320
to make decisions about how many distribution centers to open and where to locate them.

00:12:30.320 --> 00:12:35.320
This is a series of if-then decisions related to our alignment decisions. If at least one

00:12:35.320 --> 00:12:41.320
customer is aligned to a distribution center in, for example, Omaha, Nebraska, then we must

00:12:41.320 --> 00:12:46.320
open a distribution center in Omaha. The decision sets are interconnected. We cannot separate

00:12:46.320 --> 00:12:50.320
our decisions on where to locate our distribution centers from our decisions on how to align

00:12:50.320 --> 00:12:56.320
customers to distribution centers. Mathematical optimization and, more specifically, the techniques

00:12:56.320 --> 00:13:03.320
of linear and integer programming are ideal for making these kinds of interrelated decisions.

00:13:03.320 --> 00:13:07.320
When we use mathematical optimization, including for supply chain design, we're trying to minimize

00:13:07.320 --> 00:13:12.320
or maximize some equation that is the function of our decisions. In this example, Heartland Widgets

00:13:12.320 --> 00:13:17.320
wants to design the supply chain with the lowest total cost. The supply chain costs in this example

00:13:17.320 --> 00:13:22.320
are, one, the opening costs for distribution centers, which are priced at $1 million each,

00:13:22.320 --> 00:13:27.320
two, the handling costs of the distribution centers, which is one cent per unit per widget,

00:13:27.320 --> 00:13:31.320
and three, the transportation costs from distribution centers to customers, which are five cents

00:13:31.320 --> 00:13:38.320
per unit mile. Now, a unit mile is moving one unit one mile. So, for example, if you have two widgets,

00:13:38.320 --> 00:13:44.320
two units, and you move them 100 miles, that's two times 100, 200 unit miles. At five cents each,

00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:51.320
that's $10 to move two units 100 miles. You add up these three components, cost components,

00:13:51.320 --> 00:13:56.320
and that leads to the total supply chain costs that we're trying to minimize. Now, one of the

00:13:56.320 --> 00:14:02.320
tenets of supply chain design is that these cost components can be inversely related to each other.

00:14:02.320 --> 00:14:09.320
For example, the more distribution centers you have, the closer you are, on average, to your customers.

00:14:09.320 --> 00:14:14.320
And if you're closer to your customers, on average, you're going to spend less on getting the product to them

00:14:14.320 --> 00:14:21.320
on that transportation cost because it's just closer. However, the more distribution centers you have,

00:14:21.320 --> 00:14:26.320
the more you spend to open them in the first place. So, there's an inverse relationship between the distribution center

00:14:26.320 --> 00:14:31.320
opening cost and the transportation cost to get the product to your customer. The more distribution centers you have,

00:14:31.320 --> 00:14:37.320
the more it costs to open them, and the less you spend on the transportation, inverse relationship.

00:14:37.320 --> 00:14:43.320
Optimization modeling helps us figure out these relationships and help and find the optimal solution that takes into account

00:14:43.320 --> 00:14:50.320
the relationships between the costs. All right. So, because this is an R Meetup and I'm going to demo a Shiny app,

