01:00:55.320 --> 01:01:24.320
Yeah. So for optimization, the biggest ones I use is the OMPR, which stands for, I think, Optimization Modeling Process in R. I'm not sure about the P, but – and essentially, it's a pretty intuitive way to take linear program or integer program optimization models and formulate them in R. And that's kind of modeling language package. And then there's some adjacent packages that actually then send it to the solver of your choice.

01:01:24.320 --> 01:01:53.320
And so if you go on the packages GitHub site, it's very easy to read. But I like that because it's built with a tidy versus centric mindset. So for example, you use pipes to add components of your model. And you can do whatever code you need to do to prep your input tables and then just send it into your optimization model, which is how I'm able to kind of dynamically change the inputs and then reoptimize on the back end. So that's primarily what I use.

