01:17:17.319 --> 01:17:34.319
Let's see. My counterpart – well, it's just me and demand planning now. So, my boss and I, he's got a pretty good technical understanding of things. The big concern at my company – and this is not every company – is forecast accuracy.

01:17:34.319 --> 01:17:55.319
So, if the accuracy is good, if I could be doing the most complicated machine learning model that anybody ever thought of, it wouldn't make that much of a difference. But I do realize that that's not the same for everybody else. So, Ralph, you probably have a couple things to add about that or adjust about that.

01:17:56.319 --> 01:18:08.319
Yeah. I mean, it's largely like saying, okay, here's how our model solving is happening. Like, what's underneath the hood in the business sense? Here's the three cost components. Here's how you might see the tradeoffs.

01:18:09.319 --> 01:18:24.319
Sometimes it gets a little bit tricky because sometimes you see outputs that, oh, that doesn't make sense. Well, it actually does once you take into account all the constraints and things like that. But you just need to hopefully build the credibility first that they can take the hand wave explanation at that point.

01:18:25.319 --> 01:18:44.319
