01:19:00.319 --> 01:19:15.319
So that's a really good question. I would say if you have pricing data, you could put that – like price elasticity of demand, you could put that as an explanatory variable in your model. I was dealing with univariate here. And univariate is not always the best choice if you have things that correlate well.

01:19:16.319 --> 01:19:36.319
In my company, we have pricing contracts. Our price actually does not change very much, and I think our commercial team is not particularly – they don't like to change price very much, which means if you don't have enough X variation in your data, it's not going to be a good – you don't want to – you wouldn't include it in your model.

01:19:37.319 --> 01:20:01.319
So let's see. I think that mostly addressed that. But yeah, if you – I mean, the moral of the story is I think I probably – maybe I sound like a broken record here. If you can do a regression or some other type of model where you have – you're bringing other factors, do it because you're probably going to get some more information there if you find, of course, good correlation between the outcome and the predictors.

01:20:02.319 --> 01:20:15.319
