01:21:43.319 --> 01:22:02.319
I mean, a correlation matrix is a good – you know, for a start. Obviously, if you see something that's not highly correlated, you might want to consider dropping it. Academics versus business people approach things a little bit differently in terms of how they would think about a model and report that. I'm assuming your problem might be business. I don't know.

01:22:03.319 --> 01:22:26.319
But, yeah, you could – there's different methods. Maybe I should say join the ISLR book if you want to find out some more about subset selection. But correlation is a good way to get started. And then think about does it have any theoretical basis, right? If it does, then maybe you should include it. At least try it out in the beginning. But without seeing data, it's kind of hard for me to give a more in-depth answer. So hopefully that helps you out.

