01:26:57.319 --> 01:27:14.319
Yeah, yeah. I think – and I think you might – I think I'm going to miss that question in the chat earlier, so thank you for asking that. We do measure bias. Well, we have – so, the bias for – I think perhaps many of you on the call know this, but it's basically the variance over the demand, so some of all the variances.

01:27:14.319 --> 01:27:37.319
So, that is basically directionally, do you under-forecast or over-forecast? It's actually a big point of discussion right now for our commercial partners. For stat forecasts, we more focus on accuracy, but yeah, if you have the data and how we use a lot of Excel – my coworkers use a lot of Excel spreadsheets, these giant spreadsheets that, hey, it is what it is, so I work with that.

01:27:38.319 --> 01:28:00.319
So, we have OpenXLSX, so that's high times fast. It's a great package, but I can write that data in and we do track it, and it's important because I think a lot of times people do get focused on accuracy, and then I actually seen that one of our – one of our divisions, and they have a – they have this consistent bias, but they're like, well, we're only like 5% MAPE, you know, or rated MAPE.

01:28:00.319 --> 01:28:15.319
It's like, we're great. One's like, well, there's some inventory building up there. So, yes, it's really important to do, and you should be able – if you have absolute variance, you might have created a variance field, so you could potentially use that and just calculate your bias at the same time.

